gdp.label: % change
gdp.description:
This is the most obvious way to measure the health of the US economy. Recently, growth in inflation-adjusted gross domestic product has been pretty mediocre. Bush and Obama both moved into the White House during recessions, and over their combined 16 years in office GDP growth averaged a so-so 1.8% per year.

Trump takes office with the wind at his back, but he may have set himself unattainable goals. Trump has pledged to boost GDP growth to 4% or higher—a pace rarely seen outside wartime.

unemployment.label: % unemployed
unemployment.description: One of Obama’s signature economic accomplishments was a steady decline in the unemployment rate, from a high of 10% in late 2009 to below 5% at the end of his tenure. Trump has inherited a much stronger labor market than most of his predecessors, which may explain why he has repeatedly said the unemployment rate is actually 42%. The real number is much harder to improve upon.

labor.label: % active in labor force
labor.description:
The “worst labor force participation rate in 40 years” has become a popular talking point for right-wing critics of the Obama years. Labor force participation—the share of people at work or actively looking for work—fell 3.5 percentage points during Obama’s presidency.

However, it is demographic forces, rather than political ones, that are largely to blame for the decline. Trump may find it is impossible to increase labor participation, unless he manages to convince retiring baby boomers to go back to work.

poverty.label: % below poverty line
poverty.description: Rising inequality is a thorny political issue in most advanced economies, including the US. Although the percentage of Americans living below the poverty line began to improve in 2015, it remains worse than it was during most of the Bush era. For Trump, improving the lot of poor Americans is likely to be complicated by a Republican Congress eager to cut social programs in the name of reducing the deficit.

trade.label: % of GDP
trade.description: Speaking of deficits, since the 1970s the US has imported more than it exports. Trump sees a persistent trade deficit as a measure of America’s economic woes—a view disputed by most economists. Trump is intent on recapturing manufacturing jobs lost to China, Mexico, and other trade partners; he has threatened to slap tariffs on foreign goods and erect other barriers to imports of products made abroad. But success in reducing the trade deficit may lead to reduced availability and higher prices for a range of popular consumer goods.

stocks.description: The performance of the stock market is a common but problematic way to rate presidents. Although markets react to decisions made by presidents, their direct influence on them is limited. Markets responded to Trump’s election by soaring to new record highs, but time will tell whether his actual policies receive the same warm reception.

wages.label: % change from one year earlier
wages.description:
For many Americans, Obama’s presidency coincided with one of the weakest periods of wage growth in modern American history. Despite some improvement recently, many people still aren’t getting a raise—a fact that undoubtedly contributes to Trump’s populist appeal.

Unfortunately, like labor force participation, wage growth is held back by demographic changes. Trump’s proposed investments in infrastructure probably won’t boost wages in the short term, but he might just luck into it anyway.

budget.label: % of GDP
budget.description: Despite running under the Republican banner, Trump has a decidedly un-Republican attitude toward the fiscal budget. His plans to rebuild crumbling infrastructure, build a wall along the US border with Mexico, and cut taxes are all incredibly expensive. The Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget estimated that his plans would add $5.3 trillion to the federal deficit by 2026. Such commitments would make it nearly impossible to balance the budget without massive cuts to public services.
budget.source: Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis
budget.notes: OMB data no longer available on whitehouse.gov

debt.label: % of GDP
debt.description: Bush and Obama both added trillions to the public debt. Much of that was driven by borrowing related the war in Iraq and the stimulus programs put in place after the 2009 recession. Trump has backed off a plan to repay the entire debt, but reducing it remains a priority, particularly for the fiscal hawks in Congress who complained about rising debt levels throughout Obama’s presidency.
debt.source: Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis
debt.notes: OMB data no longer available on whitehouse.gov

coal.label: % change since Jan. 2000
coal.description:
One of Trump’s signature promises is to bring back jobs to coal country. This won’t move the needle for the economy as a whole, but it carries huge symbolic weight for Trump—putting down-and-out coal miners back to work is crucial to maintaining his populist appeal.

The coal industry has been in decline for many years, due to competitive prices for oil and gas and a boom in renewables. Trump may be able to prop up coal with subsidies and favorable regulation, but in doing so he could undercut jobs in other energy sectors with brighter long-term prospects.
